<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="516" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,890,1635]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1214,1239]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Females of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mello-Leitao" authorityYear="1924" box="[461,588,1214,1239]" class="Arachnida" family="Thomisidae" genus="Epicadus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubripes">
<emphasis box="[461,588,1214,1239]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">E. rubripes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Guerin-Meneville" baseAuthorityYear="1829" box="[851,1024,1214,1239]" class="Arachnida" family="Thomisidae" genus="Epicadus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heterogaster">
<emphasis box="[851,1024,1214,1239]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">E. heterogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in their stout and vertically oriented MS and in the projections above the ALE. However, they can be recognized by their “mask” pattern, which is composed of a pair of vertical dark lines on the AME and a pair of diagonal ones going from ALE to the lateral margin of the clypeus, merging to form an entire dark clypeal margin (
<figureCitation box="[959,1063,1322,1347]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1869,1891]" captionTargetBox="[184,1408,193,1859]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[184,1408,193,1859]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 16. Female specimens in vivo. A Epicadus taczanowskii (RoeWer, 1951); B Epicadus dimidiaster sp. nov.; C Epicadus rubripes Mello-Leitão, 1924 (adapted from Silva-Moreira &amp; Machado 2016: fig. 1F); D Epicadus camelinus (O. Pickard-Cambridge, 1869); E Epicadus heterogaster (Guérin-Méneville, 1829); F Epicadus trituberculatus (TaczanoWski, 1872). Photo credits:César Favacho (A); Arthur Anker (B); Almir Cândido de Almeida (C); Karl Kroeker (D); Edson Roberto (E); Edelcio Muscat (F)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1183162/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">Fig. 16C</figureCitation>
). They can also be distinguished from other species of the genus by their median posterior opisthosomal projection, which is much thicker and longer than the four lateral projections (
<figureCitation box="[604,708,1394,1419]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1869,1891]" captionTargetBox="[184,1408,193,1859]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[184,1408,193,1859]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 16. Female specimens in vivo. A Epicadus taczanowskii (RoeWer, 1951); B Epicadus dimidiaster sp. nov.; C Epicadus rubripes Mello-Leitão, 1924 (adapted from Silva-Moreira &amp; Machado 2016: fig. 1F); D Epicadus camelinus (O. Pickard-Cambridge, 1869); E Epicadus heterogaster (Guérin-Méneville, 1829); F Epicadus trituberculatus (TaczanoWski, 1872). Photo credits:César Favacho (A); Arthur Anker (B); Almir Cândido de Almeida (C); Karl Kroeker (D); Edson Roberto (E); Edelcio Muscat (F)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1183162/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">Fig. 16C</figureCitation>
). The males present vertical projections above the ALE as in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Guerin-Meneville" baseAuthorityYear="1829" class="Arachnida" family="Thomisidae" genus="Epicadus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heterogaster">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">E. heterogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, their opisthosoma has only three projections and the same color pattern as in the males of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Roewer" baseAuthorityYear="1951" class="Arachnida" family="Thomisidae" genus="Epicadus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="taczanowskii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">E. taczanowskii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Taczanowski" baseAuthorityYear="1872" box="[363,566,1466,1491]" class="Arachnida" family="Thomisidae" genus="Epicadus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trituberculatus">
<emphasis box="[363,566,1466,1491]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">E. trituberculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation box="[639,1023,1466,1491]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" refId="ref19438" refString="Silva-Moreira, T. &amp; Machado, M. (2016) Taxonomic revision of the crab spider genus Epicadus Simon, 1895 (Arachnida: Araneae: Thomisidae) With notes on related genera of Stephanopinae Simon, 1895. Zootaxa, 4147 (3), 281 - 310. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4147.3.4" type="journal article">Silva-Moreira &amp; Machado 2016</bibRefCitation>
: figs 9A–E). Their unique palp is characterized by the embolous emerging form tegulum at nine o’clock position and by RTA short and wide and DTA pointing to the apex of the cymbium (see 
<bibRefCitation box="[680,1044,1538,1563]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" refId="ref19438" refString="Silva-Moreira, T. &amp; Machado, M. (2016) Taxonomic revision of the crab spider genus Epicadus Simon, 1895 (Arachnida: Araneae: Thomisidae) With notes on related genera of Stephanopinae Simon, 1895. Zootaxa, 4147 (3), 281 - 310. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4147.3.4" type="journal article">Silva-Moreira &amp; Machado 2016</bibRefCitation>
: figs 10A–E, 
<date box="[1197,1238,1538,1563]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" value="2015-01">15I</date>
).
</paragraph>
